Exercise 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. Visualize the distribution of score in the dataframe evals.
ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = score)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Yes, it is left-skewed, which means many of students have high score

  1. Visualize and describe the relationship between score and bty_avg using geom_point() to represent the data.
ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = score, y = bty_avg)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = evals, mapping = aes(x = score, y = bty_avg))  + geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The bty_avg increases as the score increases, positive correlation. “jitter” refers to a technique used in plotting to add a small amount of random noise to the data points. The issue is that data points with the same x-values overlap, making it difficult to discern the actual density and distribution of the points.
